Pysch 755 Final

Project Overview

This project focuses on the importance of fraud detection with automotive insurance. Insurance fraud is a problem that can cost companies billions of dollars. This project focuses on the scope of automated fraud detection with different factors. In order to find this relationship, we conducted a neural network to detect when fraudulent claims were coming based on certain car characteristics.

Research Question

Can we automatically detect, with a high accuracy, a model for insurance fraud, based on the focal predictors, âauto_yearâ, âauto_makeâ and âwitnessesâ along with all of the other predictors.

Exploratory Data Analysis

data_all  <- data_all |>
  mutate(across(where(is.character), ~replace(., . == "?", NA)),
         fraud_reported = factor(fraud_reported, levels=c('N','Y')),
         property_damage_yes = if_else(property_damage == 'NO', -.5, .5),
         police_report_available_yes = if_else(police_report_available == 'NO', -.5, .5)) |> 
  select(-property_damage, -police_report_available, -'c39')

I had to change all the missing variables in the dataset from â?â to âNAâ which will make analyses smoother. As well as making âproperty_damageâ and âpolice_report_availableâ into dummy coded variables. This will also be more useful when fitting my recipes. Then removed the original variables so that the model did not try to run those variables instead of the new ones. There was an additional variables that was called âc39â, which had completely NA values in response to it, so it can removed it. In addition, fraud_reported needed to be changed to a factor in order to conduct our analysis. # Creat a Data Dictionary ## Find all variable names

Split the data

set.seed(123456)
splits_test <- data_all |> 
  initial_split(prop = .8, strata = "fraud_reported")

data_trn <- splits_test |> 
  analysis()

data_test <- splits_test |> 
  assessment()

split_val <- validation_split(data_trn, prop = c(3/4), strata = "fraud_reported")
Warning: `validation_split()` was deprecated in rsample 1.2.0.
â¹ Please use `initial_validation_split()` instead.

We use a stratified split to ensure balanced representation of fraudulent and non-fraudulent cases in both training and testing sets. The .8 proportion for training provides sufficient data for model development while reserving adequate data for final evaluation. The validation split creates a further subdivision of the training data for hyperparameter tuning and model selection, helping prevent overfitting to the test set.

Build Mode 1

Recipe Creation

rec_1 <- recipe(fraud_reported ~ auto_year + ., data = data_trn) |>
  step_rm(incident_location, insured_zip, policy_bind_date, incident_date,
          policy_number, insured_hobbies) |>
  step_impute_mean(all_numeric_predictors()) |>
  step_impute_mode(all_nominal_predictors()) |>
  step_log(policy_annual_premium, total_claim_amount, injury_claim,
           property_claim, vehicle_claim, capital_gains, offset = 1) |> 
  step_other(all_nominal_predictors(), threshold = 0.05, other = "other") |>
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) |>
  step_interact(terms = ~ injury_claim:property_damage_yes) |>
  step_interact(terms = ~ police_report_available_yes:injury_claim) |> 
  step_smote(fraud_reported) |>
  step_zv(all_predictors()) |>
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors())

feat_range_trn <- rec_1 |> 
  prep(data_trn) |> 
  bake(NULL)

This recipe implements many different step functions to allow for higher accuracy scores. We are regressing fraud_reported on all of the other variables. This is to allow our dataset to be large enough to run a model with hidden layers and not overfit to the training set. In addition, we needed to use âstep_smote()â because the data was heavily imbalanced to âNoâ for âfraud_reportedâ. By doing this, it will make our model less likely to always predict âNoâ and balance the data better.

fit_seeds <- sample.int(10^5, size = 3)

fit_nnet_range <- cache_rds(
  expr = {
    mlp(epochs = 20
)  |> 
      set_mode("classification") |> 
      set_engine("keras", callbacks = callback_early_stopping(patience = 10),
                 seeds = fit_seeds, 
                 metrics = c("accuracy", "AUC"),
                 validation_split = 0.1) |> 
      fit_resamples(
        preprocessor = rec_1,         
        resamples = split_val,        
        metrics = metric_set(accuracy)
      )
  }, 
  dir = "cache/",
  file = "fit_nnet_range",
  rerun = rerun_setting
)

Build Model 2

Recipe 2 Creation

rec_2 <- recipe(fraud_reported ~ auto_make + auto_year + witnesses + ., data = data_trn) |>
  step_rm(incident_location, insured_zip, policy_bind_date, incident_date,
          policy_number, insured_hobbies) |>
  step_impute_mean(all_numeric_predictors()) |>
  step_impute_mode(all_nominal_predictors()) |>
  step_log(policy_annual_premium, total_claim_amount, injury_claim,
           property_claim, vehicle_claim, capital_gains, offset = 1) |> 
  step_other(all_nominal_predictors(), threshold = 0.05, other = "other") |>
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) |>
  step_smote(fraud_reported, over_ratio = 1) |>
  step_zv(all_predictors()) |>
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors())

feat_range_trn <- rec_2 |> 
  prep(data_trn) |> 
  bake(NULL)

This recipe follows many of the same steps as the recipe in the first model, however, it is now not looking at any interactions. This model is a simplier model, which may yield a better result. Sometimes, more complicated models are not the better ones.

Fit nnet_m2

K Fold validation and Grid Set Up

set.seed(123233)
folds <- vfold_cv(data_trn, v = 5)

nn_grid <- grid_regular(
  hidden_units(range = c(1, 10)),
  penalty(range = c(-4, -1)), 
  levels = 4                 
)

When creating the validation of 5 v folds, this will allow our data to have a more accurate result. When folding the data 5 times, it looks for noise in other folds, not just the training set. We also created a grid in order to tune to the most optimal hyperparameters. This will save time and allow us to look for the best hyperparameters and give us the best results with these tuned hyperparameters.

fit_seeds <- sample.int(10^5, size = 3)

nnet_m2 <- cache_rds(
  expr = {
    nnet_m2_spec <- mlp(
      hidden_units = tune(),
      penalty = tune(),
      epochs = 100
    ) |> 
      set_mode("classification") |> 
      set_engine("keras", verbose = 0,
                 seeds = fit_seeds, 
                 metrics = c("accuracy", "AUC"),
                 validation_split = 0.1)
    
    tune_grid(
      object = nnet_m2_spec,
      preprocessor = rec_2,
      resamples = split_val,
      grid = nn_grid,
      metrics = metric_set(accuracy)
    )
  }, 
  dir = "cache/",
  file = "nn_m2",
  rerun = rerun_setting
)

Create best model

final_model_spec <- mlp(
  hidden_units = 10,
  penalty = 0.1,
  epochs = 64
) |> 
  set_mode("classification") |> 
  set_engine(
    "keras",
    callbacks = callback_early_stopping(patience = 10),
    verbose = 0
  )

prepped_rec <- prep(rec_2, training = data_trn)

x_train <- bake(prepped_rec, new_data = NULL) |> select(-fraud_reported)
y_train <- data_trn$fraud_reported |> factor(levels = c("N", "Y"))

prepped_rec <- prep(rec_2, training = data_trn)

train_baked <- bake(prepped_rec, new_data = data_trn)

x_train <- train_baked |> select(-fraud_reported)
y_train <- data_trn$fraud_reported |> factor(levels = c("N", "Y"))

final_model_spec <- mlp(
  hidden_units = 4,
  penalty = 0.001,
  epochs = 64
) |> 
  set_mode("classification") |> 
  set_engine(
    "keras",
    callbacks = callback_early_stopping(patience = 10),
    verbose = 0
  )

final_fit <- fit_xy(final_model_spec, x = x_train, y = y_train)

test_baked <- bake(prepped_rec, new_data = data_test)

x_test <- test_baked |> select(-fraud_reported)
y_test <- data_test$fraud_reported |> factor(levels = c("N", "Y"))

test_pred_class <- predict(final_fit, x_test)

We created a model with the most optimal hyperparameters and tested it with the test data set in order to see how it performed outside the training set data. We found that our model performed with a 82% accuracy metric.

An accuracy of 79% means that when applied to new, unseen claims data, the model correctly identifies whether a claim is fraudulent or not about 79 times out of 100. Given the imbalanced nature of the data that is a pretty decent result. However, it is important for the future to look for different performance metrics, which can tell us a more accurate interpretation of our result.
